any given collective and of the socialist household economy itself. A story of how the socialist household economy functioned, how it collapsed, and how it was remembered, this book is haunted throughout by a spectral image of the totalitarian state, whose jealous political control over the economy leads it to trample over all that which ought to be private. Underlying this image, and the neoliberal state phobia it justified, is the question of how individual interests ought to relate to the public good in a large modern society, which, it is assumed, cannot possibly function by the non-private logics of householding. This book tells the story of a large modern society that did.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunism and individualismzSoviet Union. 0aInformal sector (Economics)zSoviet Union. 0aProperty and socialism. 4aAnthropology. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  asocial history of the Soviet Union, Russian nostalgia, soviet economy, perestroika, personal rights in the Soviet Union, soviet social system, soviet project, socialist household, soviet collectivism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501770241?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501770241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501770241/